\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Antisymmetric tensor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon^{\mu_{1}...\mu_{n}}$
\end_inset

 and is a totally antisymmetric tensor .We define
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\epsilon^{01..\left(n-1\right)}=1
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and this (+
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is totally antisymmetric) completely defines 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Transformations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Physics is the same in all frames:
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../ph205FrameChange.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Change of frames
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}\rightarrow\tilde{x}^{\mu}=\Lambda_{\nu}^{\mu}x^{\nu}+a^{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 This transformation is called a Poincare transformation.
 and consists of two components:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{\nu}^{\mu}x^{\nu}$
\end_inset

 is a Lorentz transformation.
 The number of generators (the number of parameters needed to specify a
 Lorentz transformation) is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $n\left(n-1\right)/2$
\end_inset

 (this will be derived soon).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\mu}$
\end_inset

is a translation.
 The number of generators for space time shifts it is 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transformations should preserve the intervals:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
ds^{2} & = & g_{\mu\nu}dx^{\mu}dx^{\nu}\\
 & \rightarrow & g_{\mu\nu}\Lambda{}_{\rho}^{\mu}\Lambda_{d}^{\nu}dx^{\rho}dx^{d}\\
 & = & g_{\mu\nu}dx^{\mu}dx^{\nu}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

(notice that translations have no effect as 
\begin_inset Formula $dx$
\end_inset

 is a differential/difference so the translation 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 will cancel out).
 The last equality holds if
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{\mu\nu}\Lambda_{\rho}^{\mu}\Lambda_{d}^{\nu}=g_{\rho d},\label{eq:constraintLorentzTransformation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which imposes some constraints on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For infinitesimal Lorentz transformations, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{\nu}^{\mu}=\delta_{\nu}^{\mu}+\delta\omega_{\nu}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\nu}^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is identity 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\omega$
\end_inset

 describes a small rotation.
 Invariance (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:constraintLorentzTransformation"

\end_inset

) implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta\omega_{\mu\nu}=-\delta\omega_{\nu\mu}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and so there are 
\begin_inset Formula $n\left(n-1\right)/2$
\end_inset

 Lorentz generators because this is the number of parameters required to
 specify a 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 anti-symmetric matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Remarks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Poincare (Lorentz) transformations form a group (if we compose two transformatio
ns, we will get a transformation of the same kind).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We found that in 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 space-time dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{dim}\left(\mbox{Lorentz}\right)=n\left(n-1\right)/2$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{dim}\left(\mbox{Poincare}\right)=n\left(n-1\right)/2+n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrix.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{dim}\left(\mbox{Lorentz}\right)=n\left(n-1\right)/2=1$
\end_inset

 and is parametrized by one variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Lambda=\pm\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos\theta & -\sin\theta\\
\sin\theta & \cos\theta
\end{array}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Indefinite orthogonal group
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, the group of linear transformations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{\mu}\rightarrow\Lambda_{\nu}^{\mu}x^{\nu}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

that preserves a quadratic form 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 of sign 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(p,q\right)$
\end_inset

 (it has 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 positive eigenvalues and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 negative eigenvalues, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p+q=n$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q\left(x\right)=x_{1}^{2}+...+x_{p}^{2}-x_{p+1}^{2}-...-x_{p+q}^{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Such transformations are called 
\emph on
(indefinite) orthogonal group 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(p,q\right)$
\end_inset


\emph default
.
 We have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{dim}O\left(p,q\right)=n\left(n-1\right)/2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Lorentz group
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lorentz group is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mbox{Lorentz group}=\begin{cases}
O\left(n,0\right) & \mbox{corresponds to Euclidean space-time}\\
O\left(n-1,1\right) & \mbox{corresponds to Mikowski space-time}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Proper/Improper Lorentz transformations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 (which refers to Mikowski or Euclidean space metric - although in many
 papers it refers to just Mikowski metric) satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{\mu\nu}\Lambda_{\rho}^{\mu}\Lambda_{d}^{\nu}=\eta_{\rho d}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

taking the determinant we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mbox{det}\Lambda & = & 1\quad"\mbox{proper"}\\
 & \mbox{or}\\
\mbox{det}\Lambda & = & -1\quad\mbox{"improper"}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Proper Lorentz transformations form a group and is a subgroup of the group
 of Lorentz transformations.
 It is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(n\right)$
\end_inset

 for Euclidean space and 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(n-1,1\right)$
\end_inset

 for Minkowski space-time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Improper Lorentz transformations do not form a group (because composing
 two improper transformations will give us a proper transformation).
 Members of improper Lorentz transformations include 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P & = & \left(\begin{array}{cccc}
1\\
 & -1\\
 &  & -1\\
 &  &  & -1
\end{array}\right)\quad(\mbox{Parity transformtion)}\\
T & = & \left(\begin{array}{cccc}
-1\\
 & 1\\
 &  & 1\\
 &  &  & 1
\end{array}\right)\quad\mbox{(Time reversal)}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

the latter is called time reversal because it flips the sign of time.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{2}=T^{2}=1.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Generators of Transformations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How do we implement transformations (such as Lorentz transformations) in
 a Lagrangian, etc ...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Translation generator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's shift by 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\mu}:x^{\mu}\rightarrow\tilde{x}^{\mu}=x^{\mu}+a^{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding operator is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P\left(a\right)=\exp\left(iP_{\mu}a^{\mu}/\hbar\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is the generator of infinitesimal translations: 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\mu}=-i\hbar\delta_{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P\left(\delta a\right)=1-\frac{i}{\hbar}\delta a^{\mu}P_{\mu}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We have that 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{0}=-P_{0}\equiv H$
\end_inset

 is the Hamiltonian (time translation is related to conserved quantities)
 - note we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Lorentz generator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lorentz transformations are realized by unitary operators 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(\Lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 that obey 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U\left(\Lambda^{'}\Lambda\right)=U\left(\Lambda^{'}\right)U\left(\Lambda\right)\label{eq:eqU1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(as Lorentz transformations form a group and this is a representation of
 the group).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Focusing on infinitesimal transformations by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Lambda=1+\delta\omega
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We have that (definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U\left(1+\delta\omega\right)\equiv1+\frac{i}{2}\delta\omega_{\mu\nu}M^{\mu\nu}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 carries two indices so 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\omega_{\mu\nu}M^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is a contraction that gives us a scalar).
 Note that such a choice satisfies 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:eqU1"

\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\omega$
\end_inset

 is antisymmetric.
 Furthermore, we chose to contract 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 because we wanted a form for 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 that is universal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 should also obey 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U\left(\Lambda\right)^{-1}U\left(\Lambda^{'}\right)U\left(\Lambda\right)=U\left(\Lambda^{-1}\Lambda^{'}\Lambda\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 in infinitesimal form: 
\begin_inset Formula $1+\delta\omega$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda^{'}=1+\delta\omega^{'}$
\end_inset

 and expanding both sides, we get (a non-trivial solution that satisfies
 the above equation)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[M^{\mu\nu},M^{\rho d}\right]=i\left(g^{\mu\rho}M^{\nu d}-g^{\nu\rho}M^{\mu d}-g^{\mu d}M^{\nu\rho}+g^{\nu d}M^{\nu\rho}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is called the Lie algebra of Lorentz transformation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Generator of Poincare transformation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following the same exercise, we can get for a full Poincare transformation
 that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left[P^{\mu},M^{\rho d}\right] & = & i\left(g^{\mu d}P^{\mu}-g^{\mu\rho}P^{d}\right)\\
\left[P^{\mu},P^{\nu}\right] & = & 0
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

This is called the Lie algebra of Poincare transformation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{n}$
\end_inset

 space-time, there 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 parameters and the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $n\left(n-1\right)/2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Quantum Field Theory (QFT)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In contrast with classical field theory, QFT uses functionals (such as the
 action) directly rather than EOMs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Partition function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the particle-wave duality (that occurs like for example in the
 double slit experiment - 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Doubleslit3Dspectrum.gif
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - for electrons).
 The wave continuous part will help us calculate probabilities for the discrete
 entity: the particle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem of calculating probabilities relies on the fundamental ingredient
 of the partition function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Z=\int_{\mbox{possible fields}}\mathcal{D}\phi e^{-S\left[\phi\right]/\hbar}.\label{eq:qft_partition_qft}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar$
\end_inset

 is very small, we can often approximately do this integral in the saddle
 point approximation (we find configurations to satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\phi}S\left[\phi\right]=0$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Operators
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A fundamental ingredient in the theory of QFT is the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

, which can relay to us information (analogy given: thermometer), e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(x\right)=\phi\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{k}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, etc ...
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

 are combinations of basic building blocks like the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 We can have also more complicated non-local operators such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}=Tr_{R}Holy\left(A\left(x\right)\right),$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 characterizes a knot (so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

 is a function of not just one point 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Analogy between stat Mechanics and QFT
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two types of randomness appear in physics:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Quantum, when certain parameters are in the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar$
\end_inset

.
 There will be a characteristic partition function: 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:qft_partition_qft"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Thermal, with the characteristic parameter given by 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\mbox{Temperature}=\beta^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 In statistical mechanics, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=\sum_{\mbox{all configurations}}e^{-\beta E}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-\beta E}$
\end_inset

 being the statistical weight.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ising Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma=\pm1,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which characterizes spins on a lattice - to every point in space and time,
 a value is assigned.
 We can interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 as a field.
 We need to write down an action to describe the system.
 The analog of action in statistical mechanics is the energy:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E=-J\sum_{\left\langle i,j\right\rangle \mbox{ nearest neighbors}}\sigma_{i}\sigma_{j}-H\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is a good model for magnets if 
\begin_inset Formula $J>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
1D Ising Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume a circular configuration of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 spins with periodic conditions: 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}=\sigma_{i+N}$
\end_inset

.
 as shown, for example, in the figure below
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../ph205circularIsing.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Example of a cicular Ising chain
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Z & = & \sum_{\left\{ \sigma\right\} }\exp\left(\beta J\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}\sigma_{j+1}+\beta H\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

This can be solved as we have a local interaction (i.e.
 the interaction the same wherever we look at it) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the context of QFT, locality is a powerful concept and means that we
 have translational invariance.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve it, define the 
\emph on
transfer matrix
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
T & = & \left(\begin{array}{cc}
e^{\beta\left(J+H\right)} & e^{-\beta J}\\
e^{-\beta J} & e^{\beta\left(J-H\right)}
\end{array}\right)\\
 & = & \left\{ \braket{\sigma|T|\sigma^{'}}\right\} 
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and it specifies all possible values of the product 
\begin_inset Formula $\braket{\sigma|T|\sigma^{'}}$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, we can rewrite the partition function to be
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
Z & = & Tr\left(T^{N}\right)\\
 & = & \sum_{\sigma_{1}}\sum_{\sigma_{2}}...\sum_{\sigma_{N}}T_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}}T_{\sigma_{2}\sigma_{3}}...
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 can be calculated to be 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{\pm}=e^{\beta J}\left[\cosh\left(\beta H\right)\pm\sqrt{\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)+e^{-4\beta J}}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 in diagonal form, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Z & = & Tr\left(T^{N}\right)\\
 & = & \lambda_{+}^{N}+\lambda_{-}^{N}\approx\lambda_{+}^{N}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $N\gg1$
\end_inset

 and because 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{+}>\lambda_{-}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Operators in the context of the Ising Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One legitimate choice of an operator (and there is no unique choice) is
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{O}=\sigma_{i}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left\langle \mathcal{O}\right\rangle  & = & \left\langle \sigma_{i}\right\rangle =\frac{1}{Z}\sum_{\left\{ \sigma\right\} }\sigma_{i}e^{-\beta E}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{Z}Tr\left(T^{N}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & -1
\end{array}\right)\right)\\
 & = & \frac{\sinh\left(\beta+1\right)}{\sqrt{\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)+e^{-4\beta J}}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where the matrix 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & -1
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

 reflects the possible values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
We have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
Tr\left(T^{N}\right) & = & \sum_{\sigma_{1}}\sum_{\sigma_{2}}...\sum_{\sigma_{N}}T_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}}T_{\sigma_{2}\sigma_{3}}...
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
? & = & \sum_{\sigma_{1}}\sum_{\sigma_{2}}...\sum_{\sigma_{N}}\sigma_{2}T_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}}T_{\sigma_{2}\sigma_{3}}...
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

For simplicity, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}=\sigma_{2}$
\end_inset

, then we claim that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sum_{\sigma_{2}}\sigma_{2}T_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}}T_{\sigma_{2}\sigma_{3}} & = & \left[T\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & -1
\end{array}\right)T\right]_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{3}}.\\
 & \equiv & \left(TGT\right)_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{3}},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where we defined 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
G & \equiv & \left(\begin{array}{cc}
1=\sigma_{1} & 0\\
0 & -1=\sigma_{2}
\end{array}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(T\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & -1
\end{array}\right)T\right)_{ab} & = & \sum_{i}T_{ai}\left(GT\right)_{ib}\\
 & = & \sum_{ij}T_{ai}G_{ij}T_{jb}\\
 & = & \sum_{ij}T_{ai}\sigma_{i}\delta_{ij}T_{jb}\\
 & = & \sum_{i}T_{ai}\sigma_{i}T_{ib}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{\sigma_{1}}\sum_{\sigma_{2}}...\sum_{\sigma_{N}}\sigma_{l}T_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}}T_{\sigma_{2}\sigma_{3}}...=Tr\left(T^{l}GT^{k}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 are some integers.
 Using the cyclic property of the trace 
\begin_inset Formula $Tr\left(T^{l}GT^{k}\right)=Tr\left(GT^{k+l}\right)=Tr\left(GT^{N}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Compute the correlation function 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+r}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, which measures the (degree of) order of the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
The answer is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mbox{cov}\left(\sigma_{i},\sigma_{i+r}\right) & = & \frac{1}{1+e^{4J\beta}\sinh^{2}\left(H\beta\right)}e^{r/\Delta l},
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta l$
\end_inset

 is the correlation length
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta l\equiv\ln\left(\frac{\cosh\left(\beta H\right)+\sqrt{e^{-4\beta J}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}}{\cosh\left(\beta H\right)-\sqrt{e^{-4\beta J}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(Problem 1 of term a; uses ph205PS1.nb mathematica file)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The correlation function can be calculated with
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left\langle \sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+r}\right\rangle  & = & \frac{1}{Z}\left(\sum_{\left\{ \sigma\right\} }\sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+r}\exp\left(-\beta E\right)\right)\\
 & \equiv & \frac{1}{Z}\xi
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculating the partition function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I assume we have 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 spins 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We first rewrite the energy in a more convenient format.
 We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
E & = & -\beta J\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+1}-\beta H\sum_{i=1}^{n-1}\sigma_{i}\\
 & = & -\beta J\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+1}-\beta H\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n-1}\frac{\sigma_{i}}{2}+\sum_{i=1}^{n-1}\frac{\sigma_{i}}{2}\right)\\
 & = & -\beta J\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+1}-\beta H\left(\sum_{i=0}^{n-2}\frac{\sigma_{i+1}}{2}+\sum_{i=1}^{n-1}\frac{\sigma_{i}}{2}\right)\\
 & = & -\beta J\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+1}-\beta H\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n-2}\frac{\sigma_{i}+\sigma_{i+1}}{2}+\frac{\sigma_{1}}{2}+\frac{\sigma_{n-1}}{2}\right)\\
 & = & -\beta J\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+1}-\beta H\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n-1}\frac{\sigma_{i}+\sigma_{i+1}}{2}\right),\\
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where in the last equality we used the periodic boundary conditions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hence, we have thata 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
Z & = & \sum_{\left\{ \sigma\right\} }\exp\left(-\beta E\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & \sum_{\left\{ \sigma\right\} }\exp\left(\beta J\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+1}+\beta H\sum_{i}\frac{\sigma_{i}+\sigma_{i+1}}{2}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & \sum_{\left\{ \sigma\right\} }\prod_{i}\exp\left(\beta J\sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+1}+\beta H\frac{\sigma_{i}+\sigma_{i+1}}{2}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & \sum_{\left\{ \sigma\right\} }\braket{\sigma_{1}|\hat{T}_{i}|\sigma_{2}}\braket{\sigma_{2}|\hat{T}_{i}|\sigma_{3}}...\braket{\sigma_{n-2}|\hat{T}_{i}|\sigma_{n-1}}\braket{\sigma_{n-1}|\hat{T}_{i}|\sigma_{1}}\label{eq:exprTempZ}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where in the last equality we used periodic boundary conditions and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{T}_{i}=\exp\left(\beta J\hat{\sigma}_{i}\hat{\sigma}_{i+1}+\beta H\frac{\hat{\sigma}_{i}+\hat{\sigma}_{i+1}}{2}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The possible values of 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}$
\end_inset

 are given by the following transfer matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
T & = & \left(\begin{array}{ccc}
 & \sigma_{i+1}=1 & \sigma_{i+1}=-1\\
\sigma_{i}=1 & \exp\left(\beta J+\beta H\right) & \exp\left(-\beta J\right)\\
\sigma_{i}=-1 & \exp\left(-\beta J\right) & \exp\left(\beta J-\beta H\right)
\end{array}\right).
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

We will write the transfer matrix in the more concise form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
a & b\\
b & c
\end{array}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
a & \equiv & \exp\left(\beta J+\beta H\right)\\
b & \equiv & \exp\left(-\beta J\right)\\
c & \equiv & \exp\left(\beta J-\beta H\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:exprTempZ"

\end_inset

 can be simplified to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
Z & = & \sum_{\left\{ \sigma\right\} }\braket{\sigma_{1}|\hat{T}_{i}|\sigma_{2}}\braket{\sigma_{2}|\hat{T}_{i}|\sigma_{3}}...\braket{\sigma_{n-2}|\hat{T}_{i}|\sigma_{n-1}}\braket{\sigma_{n-1}|\hat{T}_{i}|\sigma_{1}}\\
 & = & \sum_{\left\{ \sigma\right\} }T_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}}T_{\sigma_{2}\sigma_{3}}...T_{\sigma_{n-1}\sigma_{1}}\\
 & = & \sum_{\sigma_{1}}\sum_{\sigma_{2}}...\sum_{\sigma_{n}}T_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}}T_{\sigma_{2}\sigma_{3}}...T_{\sigma_{n-1}\sigma_{1}}\\
 & = & \sum_{\sigma_{1}}\left(\sum_{\sigma_{n-1}}...\left(\sum_{\sigma_{4}}\left(\sum_{\sigma_{3}}\left(\sum_{\sigma_{2}}T_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}}T_{\sigma_{2}\sigma_{3}}\right)T_{\sigma_{3}\sigma_{4}}\right)T_{\sigma_{4}\sigma_{5}}\right)...T_{\sigma_{n-1}\sigma_{1}}\right)\\
 & = & \sum_{\sigma_{1}}\left(\sum_{\sigma_{n-1}}...\left(\sum_{\sigma_{4}}\left(\sum_{\sigma_{3}}\left(T^{2}\right)_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{3}}T_{\sigma_{3}\sigma_{4}}\right)T_{\sigma_{4}\sigma_{5}}\right)...T_{\sigma_{n-1}\sigma_{1}}\right)\\
 & = & \sum_{\sigma_{1}}\left(\sum_{\sigma_{n-1}}...\left(\sum_{\sigma_{5}}\left(\sum_{\sigma_{4}}\left(T^{3}\right)_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{4}}T_{\sigma_{4}\sigma_{5}}\right)T_{\sigma_{5}\sigma_{6}}\right)...T_{\sigma_{n-1}\sigma_{1}}\right)\\
 & \vdots & \vdots\\
 & = & \sum_{\sigma_{1}}\left(\sum_{\sigma_{n-1}}\left(T^{n-2}\right)_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{n-1}}T_{\sigma_{n-1}\sigma_{1}}\right)\\
 & = & \sum_{\sigma_{1}}\left(\left(T^{n-1}\right)_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{1}}\right)=\mbox{Tr}\left[T^{n-1}\right]\\
 & = & \mbox{Tr}\left[P^{-1}T^{n-1}P\right]\\
 & = & \mbox{Tr}\left[\left(P^{-1}TP\right)^{n-1}\right],
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is the unitary matrix that diagonalizes 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P^{-1}TP=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\lambda_{+} & 0\\
0 & \lambda_{-}
\end{array}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we used Mathematica to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{+}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{-}$
\end_inset

 .
 Hence, we obtain that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
Z & = & \mbox{Tr}\left[\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\lambda_{+}^{n-1} & 0\\
0 & \lambda_{-}^{n-1}
\end{array}\right)\right]\\
 & = & \lambda_{+}^{n-1}+\lambda_{-}^{n-1}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

According to Mathematica, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\lambda_{\pm} & = & \frac{a+c\pm\sqrt{4b^{2}+\left(a-c\right)^{2}}}{2}\\
 & = & e^{\beta J}\cosh\left(\beta H\right)\pm\sqrt{e^{-2\beta J}+e^{2J\beta}\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}\\
 & = & e^{\beta J}\cosh\left(\beta H\right)\pm e^{\beta J}\sqrt{e^{-4\beta J}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}\\
 & = & e^{\beta J}\left(\cosh\left(\beta H\right)\pm\sqrt{e^{-4\beta J}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}\right)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculating 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have defined that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\xi & \equiv & \sum_{\left\{ \sigma\right\} }\sigma_{j}\sigma_{j+r}\exp\left(-\beta E\right)\\
 & = & \sum_{\left\{ \sigma\right\} }\sigma_{j}\sigma_{j+r}\exp\left(\beta J\sum_{j}\sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+1}+\beta H\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}\right)\\
 & = & \sum_{\left\{ \sigma\right\} }\prod_{i}\sigma_{j}\sigma_{j+r}\exp\left(\beta J\sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+1}+\beta H\sigma_{i}\right)\\
 & = & \sum_{\left\{ \sigma\right\} }\prod_{i}\sigma_{j}\sigma_{j+r}\braket{\sigma_{i}|\hat{T}_{i}|\sigma_{i+1}}\\
 & = & \sum_{\left\{ \sigma\right\} }\braket{\sigma_{1}|\hat{T}_{1}|\sigma_{2}}\braket{\sigma_{2}|\hat{T}_{2}|\sigma_{3}}...\braket{\sigma_{j-1}|\hat{T}_{j-1}|\sigma_{j}}\sigma_{j}\braket{\sigma_{j}|\hat{T}_{j}|\sigma_{j+1}}...\\
 &  & \braket{\sigma_{j+r-1}|\hat{T}_{j+r-1}|\sigma_{j+r}}\sigma_{j+r}\braket{\sigma_{j+r}|\hat{T}_{j+r}|\sigma_{j+r+1}}...\braket{\sigma_{n-1}|\hat{T}_{n-1}|\sigma_{1}}\\
 & = & \sum_{\left\{ \sigma\right\} }T_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}}T_{\sigma_{2}\sigma_{3}}...T_{\sigma_{j-1}\sigma_{j}}\sigma_{j}T_{\sigma_{j}\sigma_{j+1}}...T_{\sigma_{j+r-1}\sigma_{j+r}}\sigma_{j+r}T_{\sigma_{j+r}\sigma_{j+r+1}}...T_{\sigma_{n-1}\sigma_{1}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Use what we did for the partition function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\xi & = & \sum_{\left\{ \sigma\right\} }\left(T^{j-1}\right)_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{j}}\sigma_{j}\left(T^{r}\right)_{\sigma_{j}\sigma_{j+r}}\sigma_{j+r}\left(T^{\underbrace{n-1-j-r+1}_{n-\left(j+r\right)}}\right)_{\sigma_{j+r}\sigma_{1}}\\
 & = & \sum_{\sigma_{1}}\left(\sum_{\sigma_{j+r}}\left(\sum_{\sigma_{j}}\left(T^{j-1}\right)_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{j}}\sigma_{j}\left(T^{r}\right)_{\sigma_{j}\sigma_{j+r}}\right)\sigma_{j+r}\left(T^{n-\left(j+r\right)}\right)_{\sigma_{j+r}\sigma_{1}}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
in the first equality, the 
\begin_inset Formula $j-1$
\end_inset

 is because we contracted everything 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1...j\right)$
\end_inset

 except for 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and the intial starting point is 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{1}$
\end_inset

 so we add 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{1+j-2=j-1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
The sum 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{\sigma_{j}}A_{i\sigma_{j}}\sigma_{j}B_{\sigma_{j}k}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(AGB\right)_{ik},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G\equiv\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
\sigma_{1}\\
 & \sigma_{2}\\
 &  & \ddots\\
 &  &  & \sigma_{n}
\end{array}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(A\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
\sigma_{1}\\
 & \sigma_{2}\\
 &  & \ddots\\
 &  &  & \sigma_{n}
\end{array}\right)B\right)_{ik} & = & \sum_{j}A_{ij}\left(GB\right)_{jk}\\
 & = & \sum_{jl}A_{ij}G_{jl}B_{lk}\\
 & = & \sum_{jl}A_{ij}\sigma_{j}\delta_{jl}B_{lk}\\
 & = & \sum_{j}A_{ij}\sigma_{j}B_{jk},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

as required.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hence, defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\sigma}$
\end_inset

by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{\sigma}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1=\sigma_{1,1}\\
 & -1=\sigma_{1,2}
\end{array}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

we can write that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\xi & = & \sum_{\sigma_{1}}\left(\sum_{\sigma_{j+r}}\left(\sum_{\sigma_{j}}\left(T^{j-1}\right)_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{j}}\sigma_{j}\left(T^{r}\right)_{\sigma_{j}\sigma_{j+r}}\right)\sigma_{j+r}\left(T^{n-\left(j+r\right)}\right)\right)\\
 & = & \sum_{\sigma_{1}}\left(\sum_{\sigma_{j+r}}\left(T^{j-1}\bm{\sigma}T^{r}\right)_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{j+r}}\sigma_{j+r}\left(T^{n-\left(j+r\right)}\right)_{\sigma_{j+r}\sigma_{1}}\right)\\
 & = & \sum_{\sigma_{1}}\left(T^{j-1}\bm{\sigma}T^{r}\bm{\sigma}T^{n-\left(j+r\right)}\right)_{\sigma_{1}\sigma_{1}}\\
 & = & \mbox{Tr}\left[T^{j-1}\bm{\sigma}T^{r}\bm{\sigma}T^{n-\left(j+r\right)}\right]\\
 & = & \mbox{Tr}\left[\bm{\sigma}T^{r}\bm{\sigma}T^{n-\left(j+r\right)+\left(j-1\right)}\right]\\
 & = & \mbox{Tr}\left[\bm{\sigma}T^{r}\bm{\sigma}T^{n-\left(r+1\right)}\right],
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where in the last equality, we used the cyclic property of the trace.
 Continuing the calculating we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\xi & = & \mbox{Tr}\left[\bm{\sigma}T^{r}\bm{\sigma}T^{n-\left(r+1\right)}\right]\\
 & = & \mbox{Tr}\left[\bm{\sigma}\left(\bm{\sigma}T^{r}+\left[T^{r},\bm{\sigma}\right]\right)T^{n-\left(r+1\right)}\right]\\
 & = & \mbox{Tr}\left[\bm{\sigma}^{2}T^{n-1}\right]+\mbox{Tr}\left(\left(\bm{\sigma}\left[T^{r},\bm{\sigma}\right]\right)T^{n-\left(r+1\right)}\right)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

What is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[T,\bm{\sigma}\right]$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mbox{Tr}\left[AB\right] & = & \mbox{Tr}\left[P^{-1}ABP\right]\\
 & = & \mbox{Tr}\left[\left(P^{-1}AP\right)\left(P^{-1}BP\right)\right]\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 be the matrix that diagonalizes 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\xi=\mbox{Tr}\left[\bm{\sigma}T^{r}\bm{\sigma}T^{n-\left(r+1\right)}\right] & = & \mbox{Tr}\left[P^{-1}\bm{\sigma}T^{r}\bm{\sigma}T^{n-\left(r+1\right)}P\right]\\
 & = & \mbox{Tr}\left[\left(P^{-1}\bm{\sigma}P\right)\left(P^{-1}T^{r}P\right)\left(P^{-1}\bm{\sigma}P\right)\left(P^{-1}T^{n-\left(r+1\right)}P\right)\right]\\
 & = & \mbox{Tr}\left[\left(P^{-1}\bm{\sigma}P\right)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\lambda_{+}^{r}\\
 & \lambda_{-}^{r}
\end{array}\right)\left(P^{-1}\bm{\sigma}P\right)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\lambda_{+}^{n-\left(r+1\right)}\\
 & \lambda_{-}^{n-\left(r+1\right)}
\end{array}\right)\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Using Mathematica, we notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(P^{-1}\bm{\sigma}P\right)$
\end_inset

 is of the form 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S\equiv\left(\begin{array}{cc}
s_{1} & s_{2}\\
s_{3} & -s_{1}
\end{array}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so using Mathematica we obtain that
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\xi & = & \mbox{Tr}\left[\left(P^{-1}\bm{\sigma}P\right)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\lambda_{+}^{r}\\
 & \lambda_{-}^{r}
\end{array}\right)\left(P^{-1}\bm{\sigma}P\right)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\lambda_{+}^{n-\left(r+1\right)}\\
 & \lambda_{-}^{n-\left(r+1\right)}
\end{array}\right)\right]\\
 & = & \mbox{Tr}\left[\left(\begin{array}{cc}
s_{1} & s_{2}\\
s_{3} & -s_{1}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\lambda_{+}^{r}\\
 & \lambda_{-}^{r}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
s_{1} & s_{2}\\
s_{3} & -s_{1}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\lambda_{+}^{n-\left(r+1\right)}\\
 & \lambda_{-}^{n-\left(r+1\right)}
\end{array}\right)\right]\\
 & = & \left(\lambda_{+}^{n-1}+\lambda_{-}^{n-1}\right)s_{1}^{2}+\left(\lambda_{+}^{r}\lambda_{-}^{n-\left(r+1\right)}+\lambda_{+}^{\left(n-\left(r+1\right)\right)}\lambda_{-}^{r}\right)s_{2}s_{3}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

In the thermodynamic limit 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 remains finite.
 We also have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{+}>\lambda_{-}$
\end_inset

, so we can write that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\xi & \approx & s_{1}^{2}\lambda_{+}^{n}+\lambda_{+}^{n-r}\lambda_{-}^{r}s_{2}s_{3}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Combining the results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+r}\right\rangle  & = & \frac{\xi}{Z}\\
 & \approx & \frac{s_{1}^{2}\lambda_{+}^{n}+\lambda_{+}^{n-r}\lambda_{-}^{r}s_{2}s_{3}}{\lambda_{+}^{n}}\\
 & = & s_{1}^{2}+\left(\frac{\lambda_{-}}{\lambda_{+}}\right)^{r}s_{2}s_{3}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Using Mathematica, this can be simplified to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
s_{1}^{2} & = & \frac{4e^{2J\beta}\sinh^{2}\left(H\beta\right)}{4e^{-2J\beta}+4e^{2J\beta}\sinh^{2}\left(H\beta\right)}\\
 & = & \frac{\sinh^{2}\left(H\beta\right)}{e^{-4J\beta}+\sinh^{2}\left(H\beta\right)}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
s_{2}s_{3} & = & \frac{1}{1+e^{4J\beta}\sinh^{2}\left(H\beta\right)}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Hence, we can write that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+r}\right\rangle  & = & \frac{\sinh^{2}\left(H\beta\right)}{e^{-4J\beta}+\sinh^{2}\left(H\beta\right)}+\frac{1}{1+e^{4J\beta}\sinh^{2}\left(H\beta\right)}\left(\frac{e^{\beta J}\left(\cosh\left(\beta H\right)-\sqrt{e^{-4\beta J}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}\right)}{e^{\beta J}\left(\cosh\left(\beta H\right)+\sqrt{e^{-4\beta J}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}\right)}\right)^{r}\\
 & = & \frac{\sinh^{2}\left(H\beta\right)}{e^{-4J\beta}+\sinh^{2}\left(H\beta\right)}+\frac{e^{-4J\beta}}{e^{-4J\beta}+\sinh^{2}\left(H\beta\right)}\left(\frac{\cosh\left(\beta H\right)-\sqrt{e^{-4\beta J}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}}{\cosh\left(\beta H\right)+\sqrt{e^{-4\beta J}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}}\right)^{r}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{e^{-4J\beta}+\sinh^{2}\left(H\beta\right)}\left[\sinh^{2}\left(H\beta\right)+e^{-4J\beta}\left(\frac{\cosh\left(\beta H\right)-\sqrt{e^{-4\beta J}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}}{\cosh\left(\beta H\right)+\sqrt{e^{-4\beta J}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}}\right)^{r}\right].
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

As expected, this does not depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 due to the translational symmetry of the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In a completely similar fashion, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \sigma\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 can be calculated by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle \sigma\right\rangle  & = & \frac{1}{Z}\mbox{tr}\left(\bm{\sigma}T^{n-1}\right)\\
 & = & \frac{1}{Z}\mbox{tr}\left(\left(\begin{array}{cc}
s_{1} & s_{2}\\
s_{3} & -s_{1}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\lambda_{+}^{n-1}\\
 & \lambda_{-}^{n-1}
\end{array}\right)\right)\\
 & = & \frac{1}{Z}s_{1}\left(\lambda_{+}^{n-1}-\lambda_{-}^{n-1}\right)\\
 & \approx & \frac{1}{Z}s_{1}\lambda_{+}^{n}\approx s_{1}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
s_{1} & = & -\frac{e^{J\beta}\text{Sinh}[H\beta]}{\sqrt{e^{-2J\beta}+e^{2J\beta}\text{Sinh}[H\beta]^{2}}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left\langle \sigma\right\rangle  & = & -\frac{e^{J\beta}\sinh\left(\beta H\right)}{\sqrt{e^{-2J\beta}+e^{2J\beta}\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}}\\
 & = & -\frac{\sinh\left(\beta H\right)}{\sqrt{e^{-4J\beta}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mbox{cov}\left(\sigma_{i},\sigma_{i+r}\right) & = & \left\langle \sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+r}\right\rangle -\left\langle \sigma_{i}\right\rangle \left\langle \sigma_{i+r}\right\rangle \\
 & = & \left\langle \sigma_{1}\sigma_{1+r}\right\rangle -\left\langle \sigma\right\rangle ^{2}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{e^{-4J\beta}+\sinh^{2}\left(H\beta\right)}\left[\sinh^{2}\left(H\beta\right)+e^{-4J\beta}\left(\frac{\cosh\left(\beta H\right)-\sqrt{e^{-4\beta J}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}}{\cosh\left(\beta H\right)+\sqrt{e^{-4\beta J}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}}\right)^{r}\right]\\
 &  & -\left(-\frac{\sinh\left(\beta H\right)}{\sqrt{e^{-4J\beta}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}}\right)^{2}\\
 & = & \frac{e^{-4J\beta}}{e^{-4J\beta}+\sinh^{2}\left(H\beta\right)}\left(\frac{\cosh\left(\beta H\right)-\sqrt{e^{-4\beta J}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}}{\cosh\left(\beta H\right)+\sqrt{e^{-4\beta J}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}}\right)^{r}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{1+e^{4J\beta}\sinh^{2}\left(H\beta\right)}\left(\frac{\cosh\left(\beta H\right)-\sqrt{e^{-4\beta J}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}}{\cosh\left(\beta H\right)+\sqrt{e^{-4\beta J}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}}\right)^{r}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{1+e^{4J\beta}\sinh^{2}\left(H\beta\right)}e^{r/\Delta l},
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta l=\ln\left(\frac{\cosh\left(\beta H\right)+\sqrt{e^{-4\beta J}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}}{\cosh\left(\beta H\right)-\sqrt{e^{-4\beta J}+\sinh^{2}\left(\beta H\right)}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Perturbation theory (Feynmann diagrams)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In QFT, one can rarely compute the partition function exactly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To do so, first decompose the action in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=S_{free\mbox{(i..e quadratic)}}+S_{interaction}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $S_{interaction}$
\end_inset

 will often depend on small parameters of the theory, which allow us to
 carry out a perturbation calculation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
As an example, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S\left[A\right]=\int\underbrace{AdA}_{S_{free}}+\underbrace{\frac{2}{3\sqrt{k}}A^{3}}_{S_{interaction}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Moreover, we can take 
\begin_inset Formula $k\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, which will give us a small parameter and will allow us to do a nice perturbati
on.
 
\begin_inset Formula $k\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 is the 'nice' perturbative limit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Take (and assume space consists of one point, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{n}=M^{0}$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S=\underbrace{m^{2}\phi^{2}}_{S_{free}}+\underbrace{\delta m^{2}\phi^{2}}_{S_{int}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the second term is a small correction to the first.
 Since we are working in 0d, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int\mathcal{D}\phi=\int d\phi$
\end_inset

 and so we have that (
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar=1$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Z=\int\mathcal{D}\phi e^{-S^{'}\left[\phi\right]=-m^{2}\phi^{2}}=\frac{\sqrt{\pi}}{m}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In our example, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
Z & = & \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{\left(m^{2}+\delta m^{2}\right)}}\\
 & = & \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{m}}\left(1+\frac{\delta m^{2}}{m^{2}}\right)^{-1/2}\\
 & = & \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{m}}\left(1-\frac{1}{2}\frac{\delta m^{2}}{m^{2}}+\frac{3}{8}\left(\frac{\delta m^{2}}{m^{2}}\right)+...\right).
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

For the simple case of 
\begin_inset Formula $S=m^{2}\phi^{2}$
\end_inset

, using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:ph205_green_simple_sol"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $G=1/m^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the free part can be written 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\left(m^{2}+\delta m^{2}\right)\phi^{2}$
\end_inset

, the exact green function will be of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $G=1/\left(m^{2}+\delta m^{2}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Analysis of the free part of the action
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\square G\left(x,y\right)=\delta\left(x-y\right),\label{eq:ph205_green_simple}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is the green's function and will turn out to be the 2-point correlation
 function (in the example of the Ising model, it is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+r}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

).
 It is called the propagator 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Use the Fourier transform: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(p\right)=\int dxe^{ipx}f\left(x\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula $\square G\left(x,y\right)=\delta\left(x-y\right)$
\end_inset

 (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:ph205_green_simple_sol"

\end_inset

) becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left(p^{2}+m^{2}\right)G\left(p\right) & = & 1
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G\left(p\right)=\frac{1}{p^{2}+m^{2}}.\label{eq:ph205_green_simple_sol}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Visualization of interactions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The effect of a simple propagator (i.e.
 one stemming from the free part of the action) can be visualized in the
 following fashion
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

