\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Introduce
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F\left(x_{ij}\right)\equiv\left(-\partial_{i}^{2}+m^{2}\right)\left(-\partial_{j}^{2}+m^{2}\right)\bm{\Delta}\left(x_{ij}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{ij}\equiv x_{i}-x_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Denote the Fourier transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{F}$
\end_inset

.
 We have according to the LSZ formula that the scattering amplitude associated
 with the second diagram in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:WJtemp"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\xi\equiv\int d^{4}x_{1}d^{4}x_{2}d^{4}x_{1^{'}}d^{4}x_{2^{'}}e^{i\left(k_{1}x_{1}+k_{2}x_{2}-k_{1}^{'}x_{1}^{'}-k_{2}^{'}x_{2}^{'}\right)}F\left(x_{11^{'}}\right)F\left(x_{22^{'}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 does the amputation then we take Fourier transform).
 Denote
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{k_{ij^{'}}}\equiv\frac{k_{i}+k_{j}}{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Continuing, we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\xi=\left(2\pi\right)^{4}\delta^{4}\left(k_{1}-k_{1}^{'}\right)\left(2\pi\right)^{4}\delta\left(k_{2}-k_{2}^{'}\right)\tilde{F}\left(\overline{k_{11^{'}}}\right)\tilde{F}\left(\overline{k_{22^{'}}}\right)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is the general structure.
 Thus due to the delta functions
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
k_{1}^{'} & = & k_{2^{'}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

means no scattering (like with first diagram in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:WJtemp"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All of this was to motivate that momentum flows in the diagrams (i.e.
 momentum is conserved).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This discussion suggests that we should consider only fully connected Feynman
 diagram (They come from 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

's acting on a single factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

), so it is convenient to work with 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 because it consists of only connected diagrams.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Connected correlation function
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Connected correlation function
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\braket{0|T\phi\left(x_{2}\right)...\phi\left(x_{E}\right)|0}_{c}\equiv\left.\delta_{1}...\delta_{E}iW\left(J\right)\right|_{J=0},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is number of external legs and the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Going back to our example of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Diagram{1^{'}fd &  & fu2^{'}\\
 & \vertexlabel_{s}p\\
1fu &  & fd2
}
$
\end_inset

, the leading order (in 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

) contribution comes from Feynman diagrams with 
\begin_inset Formula $E=4$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V=2$
\end_inset

.
 The four 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

s remove the four sources (
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

) and replace them with 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

, ...
 Note that there are 
\begin_inset Formula $4!=24$
\end_inset

 ways.
 The 24 ways are organized in three groups of 8 (as 
\begin_inset Formula $24=8\times3$
\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula $\Diagram{1fd &  & fu1^{'}\\
 & \vertexlabel_{y}f & \vertexlabel_{z}\\
2fu &  & fd2^{'}
}
$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\Diagram{1^{'}fd &  & fu2^{'}\\
 & \vertexlabel_{y}f & \vertexlabel_{z}\\
1fu &  & fd2
}
$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename C:/Users/bassa_000/Documents/GitHub/Ph205-notes/QFT notes/diagram temp 4.svg

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Notice that each group has 3 obvious reflections (so we have a symmetry
 factor of 8)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tree diagrams
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 diagrams with no closed loops so they look like a tree) all have a symmetry
 factor equal to 1: 
\begin_inset Formula $S=1$
\end_inset

.
 Note that this statement only holds once the sources have been stripped
 off and the end points labeled.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Putting everything together, we can now write that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left\langle 0|T\phi\left(x_{1}\right)\phi\left(x_{2}\right)\phi\left(x_{1}^{'}\right)\phi\left(x_{2}^{'}\right)|0\right\rangle _{c} & = & \left(ig\right)^{2}\left(\frac{1}{i}\right)\int d^{4}yd^{4}z\Delta\left(y-z\right)\\
 &  & \times\{\Delta\left(x_{1}-y\right)\Delta\left(x_{2}-y\right)\Delta\left(x_{1}^{'}-z\right)\Delta\left(x_{2}^{'}-z\right)\\
 &  & +\Delta\left(x_{1}-y\right)\Delta\left(x_{1}^{'}-y\right)\Delta\left(x_{2}-z\right)\Delta\left(x_{2}^{'}-z\right)\\
 &  & +\Delta\left(x_{1}-y\right)\Delta\left(x_{2}^{'}-y\right)\Delta\left(x_{2}-z\right)\Delta\left(x_{1}^{'}-z\right)\}+O\left(g^{2}\right)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y,z$
\end_inset

 are the endpoints of the segements, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Diagram{1^{'}fd &  & fu2^{'}\\
 & \vertexlabel_{y}f & \vertexlabel_{z}\\
1fu &  & fd2
}
$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

